Take some time to calm your mind!

The HSC Library will be hosting a meditation session every Wednesday from 12:15 until 12:45 in HSCL C3-72.  All are welcome to attend. Optional instruction in a simple, easy-to-learn mantra meditation technique will be offered from 12-12:15 on the 2nd and 4th Wednesday of the month.

December is Safe Toys and Gifts Month!  This awareness month is sponsored by the Prevent Blindness organization. View their safe toy checklist here: https://www.preventblindness.org/safe-toy-checklist 

According to the Consumer Product Safety Commission, which collects this data annually, in 2015 there were 11 fatalities and an estimated 254,200 toy-related injuries treated in US hospitals. You can read the report here: https://www.cpsc.gov/s3fs-public/Toy_Report_2015_0.pdf 

Make sure your kids stay safe this holiday season and year round by giving gifts that are age appropriate!
To sign up or find out more information about 24/7 access to the 2nd floor of the Health Science Library, click here: http://library.health.ufl.edu/about-us/library-user-policies/24hr-study-space/

Need a place free from distraction while you prepare for your exams? The Health Science Center Library has individual and group study rooms with computers and white boards for check out! They are available on a first come, first serve basis. You will need a Gator 1 card to check them out

During exams, it's important to keep your brain alert and well-functioning by getting enough rest. Use HSC Library's Energy Pods to take a break from studying.
Did you know that the Dewey Decimal System is named after Melvil Dewey? You can read a short biography of him here: http://link.galegroup.com/apps/doc/K1631001792/BIC1?u=gain40375&xid=28c98ae9
Lost anything in the HSC Library lately?  Inquire at the Information Desk on the first floor - we may have found it!

Holiday Hours!  In addition to the extended hours this Friday and Saturday, the HSC Library will have modified hours during Fall Intersession / Winter Break.  If you are planning to stay in Gainesville during the holidays, please review our hour changes to ensure you'll be able to take advantage of our resources and services.

UF Health Science Center Libraries

If you're planning on late nights as you study for finals, you can come to the HSC library this Friday and Saturday - we're open until 11:30pm!  And as always, if you have registered, our 24/7 access is available to you as well.  Registration info is available here: http://library.health.ufl.edu/about-us/library-user-policies/24hr-study-space/

Don’t forget! Tonight all of our HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest entries will be beautifully displayed at Sequential Artists Workshop's gallery during Artwalk Gainesville! Drop by between 7-10pm as part of your commemoration of World AIDS Day – enjoy some refreshments and learn more about HIV prevention and treatment. #HIVAwareUF
Education and regular testing are key parts of prevention. Learn more about how we can stop HIV together here: https://www.cdc.gov/features/LetsStopHIV/ #HIVAwareUF

Supporting friends, family, or coworkers who are HIV positive is important.  If someone you know tells you they have the virus, ACKNOWLEDGE, ASK, REASSURE, and LEARN.  For more information, https://www.hiv.gov/hiv-basics/overview/making-a-difference/supporting-someone-living-with-hiv #HIVAwareUF

Take some time to calm your mind!

The HSC Library will be hosting a meditation session every Wednesday from 12:15 until 12:45 in HSCL C3-72.  All are welcome to attend. Optional instruction in a simple, easy-to-learn mantra meditation technique will be offered from 12-12:15 on the 2nd and 4th Wednesday of the month.

To help keep HIV+ families healthy, doctors at UF College of Medicine-Jacksonville's Center for HIV/AIDS Research, Education & Services (CARES) are working to provide comprehensive pediatric and family focused treatment for HIV/AIDS.  https://hscj.ufl.edu/pediatrics/ufcares/  #HIVAwareUF

Despite all of the advances made in HIV prevention and treatment, Florida is still struggling to prevent the spread of HIV.  The Southern HIV and Alcohol Research Consortium (SHARC, http://sharc-research.org/) works with at-risk people in Florida to help prevent HIV transmission and to improve the health of people with HIV.  #HIVAwareUF

Ariel Pomputius describes the progress that doctors and scientists have made in treating HIV over the last thirty years in her HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest entry. Learn how far we’ve come, and how much farther we have to go: https://goo.gl/vwX7mB. #HIVAwareUF

In addition to looking for a vaccine for HIV, scientists at UF College of Medicine are working to improve the quality of life of those living with HIV.  This year, Dr. Carla Mavian won an award from UF to research new ways to measure the presence of HIV that don’t require a blood test.  Learn more about Dr. Mavian’s research and the award here: https://goo.gl/F92Q1M. #HIVAwareUF
World AIDS Day: Their Stories

Even if you and people you know are not HIV positive, you can still do your part to stand up to stigma. Learning more about HIV positive people living healthy lives, educating yourself about the virus, and encouraging others to do the same are small steps toward overcoming myth, stereotypes, and discrimination. https://www.hiv.gov/hiv-basics/overview/making-a-difference/standing-up-to-stigma #HIVAwareUF

Our friends at Rural Women's Health Project shared their stories with us about being HIV+ and the benefits of the Let’s Talk About It support group. The HSC Library produced this in partnership with UF Center for Arts in Medicine/UF Health Shands Arts in Medicine.  #HIVAwareUF

As part of the HSC Library’s showing of the National Library of Medicine Exhibit: “Binding Wounds, Pushing Boundaries: African Americans in Civil War Medicine”, we are proud to host Dr. William Link, author of "Southern Crucible: The Making of an American Region", as he speaks about slavery in the context of the Civil War and its implications for African Americans through the Civil Rights Movement.  Details below:

For those who might be exposed to HIV, taking PrEP on a regular basis can reduce the risk of infection. For those who know they have been exposed, taking PEP with 72-hours can reduce the risk of infection. #HIVAwareUF

Learn more at: 
https://aidsinfo.nih.gov/understanding-hiv-aids/fact-sheets/20/85/pre-exposure-prophylaxis--prep- 
https://aidsinfo.nih.gov/understanding-hiv-aids/fact-sheets/20/87/post-exposure-prophylaxis--pep-
Happy Thanksgiving!  Here are the modified HSC Library Hours this week:
Marcel Fundora challenges the stigma and myths surrounding HIV infection in his HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest entry.  Check out the full comic here: https://goo.gl/XPjTBz.  #HIVAwareUF

On Friday, Phred takes a break to read a book. Learning more about the human psyche is always on his mind!
#FriYAY! #PhrenologyPhred

Learn how to STOP: plan ahead, talk with your partners, and use protection to prevent HIV through this spoken word performance that the HSC Library made with our friends at UF Center for Arts in Medicine/UF Health Shands Arts in Medicine.  #HIVAwareUF

Despite the fact that HIV can be found in people of all ages, races, genders, and sexual orientations, there is still stigma associated with the disease. #HIVAwareUF https://www.avert.org/professionals/hiv-social-issues/stigma-discrimination

Being diagnosed with HIV can take an emotional toll.  At UF, you can get support from UF Counseling & Wellness Center, U Matter, We Care at the University of Florida (@UMatterWeCare on Twitter), and the UF Employee Assistance Program (http://eap.ufl.edu/).  #HIVAwareUF

If your friends or loved ones have recently been diagnosed with HIV, you can support them by being available to talk, listening and offering help, learning more about the virus, and encouraging treatment and medication adherence. You are an important and valuable part of creating a supportive and welcoming space. https://www.hiv.gov/hiv-basics/overview/making-a-difference/supporting-someone-living-with-hiv #HIVAwareUF

Everyone’s experience with HIV/AIDS is different – we all have our own HIV Story to tell.  By sharing our stories, we help fight the stigma of HIV.  Each of our Graphic Novel Contest entries tells a unique story. Read their stories here: http://guides.uflib.ufl.edu/graphic-novel-contest/finalists, or watch the CDC video series of HIV Stories here: https://www.cdc.gov/actagainstaids/campaigns/lsht/stories.html #HIVAwareUF

Have you been enjoying the entries from our HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest?  Come see them in person at Sequential Artists Workshop's gallery during Artwalk Gainesville on December 1st, from 7-10pm!  The HSC Library will be there with refreshments and enlarged prints of our HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest finalists.  Learn more about the Artwalk event (and get a map to the SAW gallery!) here: https://www.artwalkgainesville.com/.  #HIVAwareUF

Lisa Klug describes how a friend is overcoming the physical, emotional, and financial challenges of living with HIV.  Check out her full HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest entry here:  https://goo.gl/DxRXGi. #HIVAwareUF

Phred is ready for Friday. Hey Phred, stop hogging the nap pods!
#FriYAY #PhrenologyPhred

Right now, there is no vaccine for HIV, but scientists like University of Florida College of Veterinary Medicine's Janet Yamamoto are making discoveries that are moving us toward a future vaccine or cure.  Inducted into the Florida Inventors Hall of Fame in 2015, Dr. Yamamoto developed a vaccine for feline immunodeficiency virus (FIV) and is currently working to figure out how to make a human version.  Learn more about her groundbreaking work here: http://explore.research.ufl.edu/inventor-janet-yamamoto.html. http://post.health.ufl.edu/2013/11/22/a-virus-with-nine-lives/. #HIVAwareUF

Have you fallen for an HIV myth?  Knowledge is power: get the facts about HIV with this video, produced by the HSC Library in partnership with UF Center for Arts in Medicine/UF Health Shands Arts in Medicine.
#HIVAwareUF

A strong support network is key to overcoming the challenges of living with HIV.  Need a support group? Check out this list of support group organizations in North Florida: https://goo.gl/J2F1Es. #HIVAwareUF

Tell us how the library can support your use of technology!

What kind of smartphone or tablet are you using? What apps and web-based resources are you using? How can your library support your use of technology? The Health Science Center Libraries would like to know how you, our Health Science Center patrons, use technology in your daily work and study. Please participate in our brief survey on this topic:

https://ufl.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_38EE27gGwXwfKId 

This is an annual survey; you may have taken it before – if so, please take it again.  The information obtained will help the HSC Libraries improve our services in this ever-changing arena. The survey is anonymous, voluntary, and will take 5-10 minutes to complete

Get to know the 3 types of HIV treatment (as illustrated by Kelena Klippel): ART, PrEP, and PEP!  Antiretroviral therapy is a combination of drugs that keeps HIV+ people healthy, PrEP helps prevent people at risk of infection from getting HIV, and PEP can help keep someone recently exposed to HIV from getting infected.  Learn more here: https://aidsinfo.nih.gov/understanding-hiv-aids/fact-sheets/21/51/hiv-treatment--the-basics. #HIVAwareUF

In her comic, “Through Massaman’s Eyes”, Kelena Klippel demonstrates the importance of self-care and community after being diagnosed with HIV.  Check out her full HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest entry here: https://goo.gl/fXWXpP.  #HIVAwareUF
A library is the perfect place to spend a Friday night…if you’re a bookworm! #FriYAY!

Keep yourself and your partners safe and healthy – know your HIV status!  There are lots of places you can get confidential testing: GatorWell Health Promotion Services, UF Student Health Care Center, UF HealthStreet, and more!  Check out HIV.gov’s testing locator for more: https://locator.hiv.gov/. #HIVAwareUF

Over the next few weeks we’ll be introducing our HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest finalists and their exciting and creative entries, so be on the lookout!  If you want to get a head start you can check out all of the entries on our HIV/AIDS Library Guide here: http://guides.uflib.ufl.edu/graphic-novel-contest/finalists. #HIVAwareUF

In preparation for World AIDS Day on December 1st, and as a culmination of our HIV/AIDS Graphic Novel Contest, the HSC Library will be sharing information, resources, and artwork related to HIV/AIDS throughout the month of November.  The artwork will includes panels and pages from entries from all of our contest entrants, including our winner: Lisa Klug, for her entry, “My Journey with AIDS”.  Congratulations Lisa, and a big thank you to everyone who participated, including our guest judges from the Sequential Artists Workshop!
Speaking of SAW, if you’re interested in viewing the amazing artwork of our finalists in person, come visit SAW’s exhibition space during the Artwalk Gainesville on December 1st, from 7-10pm.  We’ll be serving refreshments & displaying enlarged prints of our Graphic Novel Contest finalists.  Celebrate World AIDS Day by viewing and hearing the stories of local artists impacted by HIV.  Help create an #HIVAwareUF!

How can we help patients with limited health literacy? 

Recognize the signs.  Know sources for easy to read, multi-language, or graphic health information.  Employ strategies such as Teach Back or Plain Language to activate patient engagement.

What are the costs of limited health literacy? 

Patients with limited health literacy use less preventive medicine but more emergency services. They have increased hospital admissions and longer stays. They have decreased health status and poor health outcomes.  All in all, patients with limited health literacy cost the healthcare system over $200 billion a year-that’s enough to provide healthcare to over 47 million uninsured Americans.

Would you recognize the signs of limited health literacy in your patient? Though health literacy often correlates to education level, socioeconomic status and insurance status, and racial/ethnic disparities, you can’t tell by looking.

October is Health Literacy Month!  

Health literacy is the degree to which individuals have the capacity to obtain, process, and understand basic health information and services needed to make appropriate health decisions. (Healthy People 2010: http://www.healthypeople.gov/2010/)

Have you packed your digital disaster supply kit?  It's important to be able to access the information you need in an emergency, whether you're a first responder or simply trying to connect with separated family members.  

But don't worry, the Disaster Information Management Research Center has put together a list of mobile apps that can help in a disaster scenario: https://sis.nlm.nih.gov/dimrc/disasterapps.html.

September 18th – 22nd marks the 8th annual Postdoc Appreciation Week.  The UF Health Science Center Library is proud to host a meet and greet for health science center postdocs.  Come unwind, eat breakfast, get caffeinated, celebrate your achievements, connect with other postdocs, and learn about Health Science Center Library resources and services before you embark on your research adventures for the day!

It seeks to cultivate awareness of, and support for, this ever-growing community of learners and to celebrate the future of online education—wherever technology and our imaginations take us!

What's in your disaster supply kit?  It doesn't have to be just food, water, and first aid equipment.   Books, games, and hard candy are supplies that can help keep you and your family calm and entertained during an emergency.  Learn more about what you can include in your kit here: https://www.ready.gov/build-a-kit.  

What do you think librarians would include in their disaster supply kits?

Did you know that after a disaster, libraries often serve as safe refuges, providing information and resources to help their communities recover? 

 How can you help your community recover from a disaster?  One way is to get involved in your local Community Emergency Response Team (CERT).  

Learn more about the Alachua County CERT here: http://www.alachuacounty.us/Depts/EM/ServicesandPrograms/pages/cert.aspx
